    <title>Combined summary - How accurate are the Bitcoin timestamps?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T00:22:56.532385+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-January/015677.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The accuracy of timestamps in Bitcoin is a critical aspect to ensure the integrity of the blockchain. While there are mechanisms to control the accuracy of Proof of Work (PoW), the assumption that a majority of miners are honest is questioned by some due to the financial incentive for dishonest miners to manipulate timestamps.One possible improvement suggested is exchanging average with standard deviation in the difficulty adjustment formula to better reflect changes in hash power. Additionally, using the median of the last 11 blocks is mentioned as an improved indicator of actual real-time for check locktime. However, both improvements assume that a majority of miners are honest.NTP (Network Time Protocol) is currently used for time synchronization in Bitcoin mining, but it has been subject to security vulnerabilities in the past and can potentially expose systems to various attacks. Alternative protocols and methods, such as Network Time Security (NTS), provide better security.When it comes to check locktime, the median of the last 11 blocks is used as an indicator of what the actual real time is, assuming a majority of miners are honest. Open-timestamp calendar servers also provide more precise time-stamping under the assumption that the server is behaving correctly.In conclusion, while the accuracy of timestamps in Bitcoin is crucial, there are concerns about the validity of the assumption that a majority of miners are honest regarding timestamp manipulation. Various improvements have been suggested, but they rely on this assumption. It may be advisable for Bitcoin miners to consider adopting more secure time synchronization methods to ensure the continued security and integrity of the blockchain. Permissioned consensus protocols, such as Hyperledger, have no timestamps.</summary>
